            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Kai Roshan was born from a union of precision and artistry. The only child of an Iranian mechanical engineer and a Japanese ceramicist, he grew up in Berkeley, where his world was split between his father\u2019s garage, filled with calipers and schematics, and his mother\u2019s studio, fragrant with wet clay and glazing chemicals. This dual inheritance shaped him profoundly; he learned to respect both the unyielding logic of materials and the fluid beauty of form.\n\nHis path led him to the California College of the Arts for a degree in Industrial Design. However, post-graduation, he found the corporate design world felt hollow. He chafed at creating renderings for products he would never touch. A key turning point came during a brief, soul-crushing stint designing ergonomic office chairs. He quit, took a pay cut, and found a job as a junior fabricator in a small metalworking shop. He was home. Over the next fifteen years, he honed his craft, mastering welding, CNC machining, and complex assemblies, eventually becoming the Lead Fabricator for a high-end manufacturing firm in Dogpatch that creates custom architectural elements and large-scale art installations.\n\nToday, Kai\u2019s life is a study in deliberate construction. He lives in a meticulously organized apartment in the Mission District with his partner of twelve years, Marco, a landscape architect. His daily routine begins with a strong cup of coffee and the 3.5-mile bicycle ride to work, a meditative journey that cuts through the industrial bones of the city he loves. He finds beauty in the transition from the Mission\u2019s vibrant murals to Potrero Hill\u2019s quiet inclines and Dogpatch\u2019s warehouse facades.\n\nThough content, Kai feels a familiar restlessness. His hands, calloused and capable, want to build something of his own. His quiet dream is to open a small, collaborative workshop\u2014a space that merges his father\u2019s engineering heritage with his mother\u2019s artistic soul. He envisions a studio where designers, artists, and engineers can come together not just to design, but to build, creating tangible objects of lasting value and beauty in a city increasingly defined by the ephemeral."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was nine when his mother\u2019s most cherished chawan\u2014a hand-thrown tea bowl\u2014slipped and shattered on the tile floor. His father produced epoxy and calipers, mapping a precise repair. But his mother brought out a tiny kit with gold powder and lacquer. Kai sat between them, watching her trace the cracks not to hide them, but to celebrate them with veins of gold. It was the first time he understood that to fix something and to heal it were two different, equally beautiful acts. The memory became the blueprint for his entire philosophy.\n\n2.\nAt 24, in a soul-crushing corporate job, he stared at a projection of his latest design: an ergonomic office chair. A senior designer was droning on about optimizing the lumbar curve by 3.8%. Kai felt a profound hollowness. He had never touched a prototype, only pixels. He\u2019d spent months rendering a ghost of a thing he would never build or feel. The next morning, he quit. That sterile meeting room taught him that his hands needed to be as involved as his mind, or he would simply break.\n\n3.\nThe first day at the metal shop was a sensory assault that felt like coming home. The sharp, electric smell of ozone from a TIG welder, the high shriek of the chop saw through steel, the cool, weighty heft of an unfinished piece in his hands. He was just sweeping floors and deburring edges, the lowest man on the totem pole, yet he felt a rightness he\u2019d never known. This was real. The noise, the grit, the tangible weight of creation\u2014it was the language his soul spoke.\n\n4.\nOn their third date, he walked with Marco through the San Francisco Botanical Garden. Marco stopped not at a flower, but at the base of a huge tree fern. He gently traced the fractal pattern of the unfolding fronds, explaining the structural logic, the efficient unfurling of its design. In that moment, watching Marco read the architecture of a living thing, Kai felt a deep click of recognition. He wasn't just falling for a man; he was falling for a way of seeing the world that mirrored his own.\n\n5.\nRiding his bike through Dogpatch last spring, he saw it: a small, brick-faced warehouse with grimy, multi-paned windows. A faded \u201cFor Lease\u201d sign was zip-tied to the security gate. In the morning light, he could suddenly envision the entire space\u2014welding bays on one side, a clean room for assembly on the other, with a large communal table in the middle. The specific image was so powerful, so complete, that it changed his quiet dream into a tangible, urgent need. It gave his restlessness an address."
